124. quos mittit porta Syenes] Syene being a frontier town in Upper Egypt, through which the traffic from Aethiopia

, is called ‘portae So above he speaks of “Idumaeae Syrophoenix incola portae '' (viii. 160, if the verse be genuine, which I doubt). The Nabathaei and Idumaei were not very clearly distin- guished at the time Juvenal wrote, parts of Arabia Petraea being occupied by each. Arabia never produced elephants, and they are not now found and perhaps never were in the north of Africa. The elephant dropping his tusks when they grow too large for him is afable. Pliny tells one or two more (H. N. viii. 3).
